"or cutting the enemy off from its sources of food. \n# Errors\nThe most common error relief agencies make is to use a group of malnourished people as the basis for determining a strategy of action. Of course, it has been shown that mortality is directly related to the severity of malnutrition. In an emergency, then, the malnourished members of the population merit particular attention. Today's nutritional rehabilitation programs are well-organized and capable of achieving good results quickly. Without a broader strategy encompassing the maintenance of family food security, however, rehabilitated children will find themselves back in a dysfunctional food system where families' basic needs are not covered."